               <interp inst="t18470920-2236" type="uri" value="sessionsPapers/18470920"></interp>
               <interp inst="t18470920-2236" type="date" value="18470920"></interp>
               <join result="criminalCharge" id="t18470920-2236-charge-1" targOrder="Y" targets="def1-2236-18470920 t18470920-2236-offence-1 t18470920-2236-verdict-1"></join>
               <p>2236. <persName id="def1-2236-18470920" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def1-2236-18470920" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-2236-18470920" type="age" value="54"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-2236-18470920" type="surname" value="OLDS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-2236-18470920" type="given" value="JOHN AUGUSTUS"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">JOHN AUGUSTUS OLDS</hi>
                  </persName> was indicted<rs id="t18470920-2236-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18470920-2236-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="kill"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18470920-2236-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="manslaughter"></interp> for feloniously killing and slaying <persName id="t18470920-name-1175" type="victimName">
                        <interp inst="t18470920-name-1175" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470920-name-1175" type="surname" value="OLDS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470920-name-1175" type="given" value="MARY"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18470920-2236-offence-1 t18470920-name-1175"></join>Mary Olds</persName>; He was <hi rend="italic">also</hi> charged upon the Coroner's Inquisition with the like manslaughter.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. PAYNE</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">conducted the Prosecution.</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18470920-name-1176" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18470920-name-1176" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470920-name-1176" type="surname" value="GOWAR"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470920-name-1176" type="given" value="FREDERICK RICHARD"></interp>FREDERICK RICHARD GOWAR.</persName>
                  </hi> I am a surgeon, in the Old Kent-road. I knew the deceased Mrs. Olds very well—I was called to see her on the Thursday, the day she died—I had attended her before, for violet cough, occasional spitting of blood, and irritability of the lungs—it was a pulmonary complaint—my first observation of her on this occasion was on the Wednesday morn<lb></lb>ing, 25th of Aug., when she came to my house, and complained of violent pain in her chest and about the stomach, and vomiting of blood at times—while she was in my house she spat up a good deal of blood—I never knew her spit blood before—she had frequently complained of cough and cold—she complained of being hurt about the throat, and being held and pressed about the chest—I saw the throat—the skin appeared a little reddened, as if com<lb></lb>pressed, but there was nothing particularly marked about it—it seemed redder</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184709200199"></xptr>
               <p>than it ought to be—there were no bruises—it was only red in one part—the left temple was bruised—that seemed to have been the effect of some violence—it was rather a lasting bruise, but not of itself likely to occasion death—I prescribed for her, and directed her to take everything very cold—I was sent for to her the next day, between one and two o'clock, and she was dead—I was prevented from seeing her in the morning—there was venous blood about the mouth—it seemed to come from the lungs—it was of a dark colour—by the direction of the Coroner I made a <hi rend="italic">post-mortem</hi> examination—the appearance of the lungs was very unhealthy—the upper part of each lung was very congested, very loaded with extravasated blood, the bronchial vessels also very loaded with blood and the aesophagus—the blood in the lungs was partly fluid and partly coagulated—the liver was very unhealthy, of a very dark colour instead of its natural colour—there was a flaxidity about it, which showed a great deal of unnatural character—the gall-bladder was almost empty—there was scarcely any bile in it—it contained a little air apparently—the stomach appeared partially inflamed about the upper part, and there was a great deal of blood mixed with fluid of the stomach—it must have come into the stomach from the trachea—the vessels were very loaded with blood, not rup<lb></lb>tured, but the arteries of that part are so minute, in all probability the blood might have come in partially from the veins of the stomach—that would not account for the whole—a large quantity must have come from the lungs, and got down the throat—the spleen and other organs were not quite healthy—there did not appear any inflammation about the bowels in general—the principal seat of disorder appeared the lungs and liver, and the irregular state of the bladder—in my opinion the flow of blood from the lungs arose from violence by blows or falls—the lungs being in a weak state they were susceptible—I can undertake to say that violence must have produced those effects—they could not have been produced to that extent without violence.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. BALLANTINE.</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> How long had you attended this poor woman? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Several times in the course of the summer—she had taken medicine—she had stated to me before this that she had spit small quantities of blood, not to any extent—she told me that she occasionally expectorated blood—I mean by that, thrown it from her lungs—that might probably be occasioned by ulceration—there must have been some lesion of ves<lb></lb>sels to give rise to it—there may be a lesion without a rupture, or the evacuation of blood, but it generally happens—I am able to say that the blood evacuated was venous blood, and not arterial—I did not ascertain what vessel was broken—there were a variety of vessels, towards the upper part of the lungs, not any of the main vessels—there is no difficulty in ascertaining whether blood is venous or arterial—the colour of venous blood is dark, and arterial blood is red or florid—at the upper part of the lungs, the veins and arteries mix and inter<lb></lb>sect—I can hardly say that there were no arterial vessels ruptured, probably there might have been, but the greater amount was venous blood—I cannot say whether that was from the diseased part of the lung, as the lungs alto<lb></lb>gether were very weak, and participated in point of texture to a similarity of construction—there had been ulceration—it occasionally happens with the lungs in such a state, that the cough may rupture the vessels and produce great extravasation of blood—it is almost universally the mode in which such patients die—I know that the deceased was subject to a frequent cough—I do not consider, from the appearances of the lungs, that a violent fit of coughing would have produced the great effusion that I witnessed; the lungs were apparently not in that very tender state as to produce it—they were in a weakened state—external violence must be a considerably greater strain</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184709200200"></xptr>
               <p>upon the lungs than a cough—it must in my opinion have been done by a violent concussion which jarred the vessels, and gave rise to the ruptures—such a concussion might be occasioned by a violent cough under a very much more diseased state of lings, but I do not consider these lungs were in that state—none of the main vessels were ruptured, only the smaller once—they would be very tender, and were in a delicate state.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Suppose she had died from any other cause than the rupture, and you had seen these lungs without the extravasation of blood upon them, should you have said they were at all safe even from day to day? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes—I should not consider they were in such a weak state as to give way—I should not consider that a violent cough would have been likely to affect them at all</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Evan though you had heard that she had been in the habit of spiting blood? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> The answer to that question would depend entirely upon the examination of any particular part which might be diseased—I believe har age was about forty odd, I cannot say exactly, from forty to fifty—she might have been fifty-two—the blood in the stomach had come from the lungs, got into the trachea, and so passed into the stomach.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. PAYNE.</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Do I understand you rightly, that the state of the lungs was not in your opinion such as to lead you to conclude that a mere fit of coughing would have ruptured the vessels, and have produced the quantity of blood you saw? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes—if on the Saturday night pre<lb></lb>vious to my seeing her, she had been thrown down on the ground, and held there, I should consider that would account for the rupture of the vessels I saw.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT.</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Were there many ulcers on the lungs? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Not a great many, there were four or five patches of ulceration—sometimes the efflux of blend arises from ulceration eating into the vessels, opening the surface of the vessels themselves; and sometimes a vessel will burst or rupture from con<lb></lb>cussion, by reason of its weakness—it was quite impossible for me to in<lb></lb>vestigate the number of opening through which the blood might have flowed, there was such a large accumulation in the parts that it was nothing but a mass of blood, intermixed so firmly in the upper part of the lungs with the trachea, and so on, that it was a complete choak as it were—I divided the lungs in my examination, but could discriminate the openings, the vessels are so very minute there—suffocation was the immediate cause of death by the vomiting of blood into the mouth, choaking the passage—she was cough<lb></lb>ing at the time she came to me in the morning from the quantity of blood that was rising in her throat—I had never seen her so violently troubled by a cough before—I had seen her about a fortnight before—I did not observe any more chance of her dying then, than I had observed at other periods when I had seen her—if I had heard next morning that she had been taken with a violent cough which had ended in suffocation by blood, I should have been very much surprised—she was not in that condition—she was generally emaciated, with weak powers, and had been in a bad state of health for several years—there was no accounting for the state of the liver, lungs, spleen, and gall-bladder—there was peculiar constitutional irregularity—I had know her for many years, and she was a very regular, quiet, domestic person—the liver may be disordered by a habit of drinking—there were appearances that would arise from irregular habits, but I never saw her intoxicated, or sup<lb></lb>posed she was addicted to drinking—I always considered her a woman of feeble habits, weak about the lungs, with an unnatural state of liver, and no on—the ordinary immediate cause of death from pulmonary complaints is from inflammation of the substance of the lungs, producing matter, so that</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184709200201"></xptr>
               <p>they expectorate <hi rend="italic">pus</hi> and in proportion to the number of ulcers on the sur<lb></lb>face of the lungs, so in the same ratio will a person become sooner or later destroyed—it is a diminution of the powers of life—the process of ulcera<lb></lb>tion going on in the lungs must necessarily furnish blood to support those inflammatory parts, and thus nature is robbed of a very great support—it decays the functions of the lungs—I examined the deceased's body externally—I did not perceive any marks of violence except that on the left temple and the throat.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18470920-name-1177" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18470920-name-1177" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470920-name-1177" type="surname" value="WILCOXON"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470920-name-1177" type="given" value="LOUISA"></interp>LOUISA WILCOXON.</persName>
                  </hi> I am the wife of Henry Wilcoxon, a brush-maker, living at 1, Wood's-court, John-street, Newington—I knew the deceased Mrs. Olds and her husband, they lived in the next house to me. On the Saturday night the 21st Aug., I was in my own back room, and was disturbed by a fall, and a cry of murder—I heard the fall first—the deceased and her husband slept in the up-stairs front room—the fall appeared to be in their back room—I heard Mrs. Olds cry "Murder"—I then ran to my door and opened it—the cries were still going on—they then appeared to come from the front room—I went up stairs into my front room, and opened the window, and then heard Mr. Olds say something to his wife, but what it was I could not understand—I heard her crying—I did not hear her say anything—it appeared to me as though he was still beating her—I did not see him—I judged by her cries that he was beating her—I did not hear the sound of blows just then—I saw their son William pass my door as I opened it—he came from his father's house—I saw him come back with a policeman—after the policeman was gone, I heard Mr. Olds beating his wife again—I heard the blows—the policeman stayed, I should think, about five minutes—I heard Mrs. Olds say, "You brute," you brute," several times, that was after I heard the sound of blows—there was no one there but the boy William, Mr. Olds, and his wife—I only heard the one fall, the other was hitting—I saw the deceased about four o'clock on the afternoon of the next day (the Sunday) in the back yard—she was very ill then—I saw her again on the Monday in the back yard, and saw marks on her throat—I did not see them on Sunday—I was nearer to her on Monday than I was on the Sunday—she had a bruise on the left temple—I had seen her about the middle of the day on the satur<lb></lb>day—she had not any bruise on the left temple then—I was her on the Wednesday and Thursday—she was very ill each day—each day she got worse—I saw her at the sink vomiting blood—she called me to see it—I had not seen her spit blood before the Saturday—she had not been well for some time before—after the Saturday night I observed a very great change in her—it continued up to Thursday, when she died—I saw her on the morning she died, at nine o'clock, not after that—she died at half-past two—I ran in when she was dying.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> Were you intimate with her? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes—I generally saw her every day—she used to go out washing I believe—she did not go out to wash after this, and had not been for some weeks before, in consequence of the state of her heath—she said she had no strength—she appeared not well—she had a very bad cough—it was a very teasing cough, lasting for some minutes at a time—it appeared to strain her and try her very much—I did not see that she spat blood when she coughed—I have seen her spit after the coughing, but have not noticed whether there was—blood or not—it did not seem to be matter—she was a very sober woman—I never saw her the worse for liquor—I heard the prisoner say something to her, but what it was I could not understand—he was tipsy—when he was tipsy I could not understand him—he was tipsy on Saturday night.</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184709200202"></xptr>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. GOWAR</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">re-examined.</hi> Hemorrhage on the lungs produced by violence does not diminish in general—I never knew it do so—if the violence was great I should think it likely that the hemorrhage would continue; but there are so many shades, it depends entirely upon the degree of violence, and the injury occasioned by that violence—in this instance it seemed to increase, under a cer<lb></lb>tain state it would diminish—the natural tendency would be to heal—I do not consider the blow on the temple likely to have produced this hemorrhage—I attribute the redness of the neck to squeezing—that alone was not sufficient to occasion the hemorrhage, nor do I consider that the two combined were sufficient—there was no evident mark of any blow, or pressure, or violent impact on the head—there was extravasation about the neck and shoulder, resulting from the following of the blood from the lungs, but that was from the position of the body after death—if she was seized by the throat, and forced violently upon the ground, I think that might have produced the mischief, by a violent <hi rend="italic">jarring</hi> of the system—if that might were so, it would be natural to ex<lb></lb>pect to find some mark on the back, but I saw none, nor any bruise—a per<lb></lb>son might be pushed down, and receive a violent inward shock, without any external appearance of it whatever—I cannot say that the same concussion would be produced, if in a struggle she fell down, as if she had been thrown down and pressed upon—I found nothing to indicate that she had been cut down and passed upon.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18470920-name-1178" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18470920-name-1178" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470920-name-1178" type="surname" value="OLDS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470920-name-1178" type="given" value="ELIZA"></interp>ELIZA OLDS.</persName>
                  </hi> I am the wife of Joseph Olds, a bricklayer, and live at No. 3, John-street, next door to the prisoner; I married his son. On the satur<lb></lb>day night before the deceased's death I heard a piece of work there—the youngest boy, William, came to me; and, in consequence of what he said I went in—I found the prisoner and the deceased there alone—the deceased opened the door the moment I got there, and the prisoner shut it again—the deceased went towards the door again—the prisoner would not let her open it—he took her round the waist, and she fell down—she desired me to open the window—I jumped on the table to open it, and Mr. Palmer jumped in at the window—he lives in the same street—my mother was then on the floor by the front door, and my father by her—I do not know whether he had hold of her or not—in my fright I did not see—I do not know how she got on the floor—she was not on the floor when I jumped on the table to open the win<lb></lb>dow, but when I opened it and Mr. Palmer jumped in, she was, and the prisoner had hold of her, I did not see in what way—Mr. Palmer went away before I did—I remained with the deceased—my husband came in, and took the pri<lb></lb>soner away—he was gone about an hour and a half—I had not seen the de<lb></lb>ceased on the Friday—I had seen her on the Thursday—I was with her on the Sunday—she did not appear to be very well then—she complained of being very stiff and sore—she was up, and down stairs on Monday, Tuesday, and Wednesday, and on the Thursday also—she seemed as if she got very weak and had—she had been very ill for a long time, and getting worse—she had been getting weaker and weaker every day up to this times—she got worse and worse from the Sunday till the Thursday—she died about half-past two o'clock on the Thursday—she was choked, through vomiting blood—I went for the doctor, but she was dead before he came—the prisoner was quite tipsy on the Saturday night.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> While you were in the room, you did not see your father strike your mother at all? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No, I did not see any blows—I did not see him use any violence at all towards her while I was there—she did not call out as if any violence was used towards her, but I did not come up till it was over—when the deceased was on the ground I do not know whether the</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184709200203"></xptr>
               <p>prisoner was trying to help her up or not—I had observed the deceased spit<lb></lb>ting during the last eight or nine months, and every time she spat she spat blood—that had been increasing—she said she spat more every day, I did not see it—I had seen her spit blood before this Sunday, but not that quantity that she did at last—I saw her spit blood on the Monday night—I do not know whether she did so on the Saturday—I did not see her till the Saturday night—I saw her spit a little on the Sunday—she spat more blood on the Monday than she had done before—not a great deal more—I had never seen her spit so much before—the prisoner was almost always very kind to her, and to me and the rest of the family, for whatever I saw.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. PAYNE.</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> You did not live with him? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No Monday night, and—I did not see the deceased at the sink on the Monday—I saw her on the saw her spit blood in the fire-place—I had seen her spit blood before the Saturday—she mostly spat it as she sat by the fire-place—there was mostly phlegm with it—I never saw anything like what occurred on the day she died, or like what occurred on the Monday night.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT.</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Was it worse on Monday than it was on Sunday. <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes; it was getting worse every day, and on the Thursday she was suffocated—on the Sunday I observed a bruise on her forehead, over the eye—I saw no mark on her neck—she never showed me any mark—I never saw it—I did not see it after her death.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. PAYNE.</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> How was she dressed about the throat? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> She had a gown that came high up in the neck, and she always had a handkerchief on under that, so that you could not see her neck—I did not see the body after death—my mother was with her when she died—I was not—her name was Mary.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18470920-name-1179" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18470920-name-1179" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470920-name-1179" type="surname" value="PALMER"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470920-name-1179" type="given" value="WILLIAM HENRY"></interp>WILLIAM HENRY PALMER.</persName>
                  </hi> I am a bricklayer, living in John-street—I knew the deceased. On the Saturday night before she died, about half-past nine o'clock, I was standing at my own door, and heard a noise from the court where the prisoner lived—I went to the house, and found the prisoner and his wife quarrelling—the wife said to me, "For God's sake, take him away; for I am afraid he will kill me," or something to that effect—I went in on two occasions—the first time I went in by the door, nobody was there then but the prisoner and his wife—I remained about five minutes that time—I said to the prisoner, "What is all this notice about?"—he said, "Oh, it is all right, old fellow!"—I said, "Well, put on your jacket, and come out with me; what is the use of quarrelling?"—he said, "No, I will go up stairs to bed"—I then came out—I went again from a quarter to half-an-hour afterwards, because there was a second disturbance—the door was shut then, and I got in by the window—I then saw the prisoner, the deceased, and the last witness in the room—I was there scarcely a minute that time—the son came in, and directly he came in I came out—the deceased seemed in a dreadfully agitated state, the first time I went in; and so did the prisoner.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> Did she complain of having received any injury or any violence whatever? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> She did not, she mad no complaint of any kind, no further than saying, "Take him away"—he appeared to have been drink<lb></lb>ing too much, and was in a very excited state.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18470920-name-1180" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18470920-name-1180" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470920-name-1180" type="surname" value="KILLEEN"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470920-name-1180" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN KILLEEN</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">policeman, P</hi> 309.) On the Saturday night in question the prisoner's son came to fetch me, and I went to the house about half-past nine o'clock—I saw the deceased there, and no one else—I saw a bruise on her face, I believe over the right eye; she drew my attention to it—that</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184709200204"></xptr>
               <p>was all she pointed out to me, and all I observed—she made a complaint to me, but did not charge anybody.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18470920-name-1181" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18470920-name-1181" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470920-name-1181" type="surname" value="NORTON"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470920-name-1181" type="given" value="ANN"></interp>ANN NORTON.</persName>
                  </hi> I am the wife of Stephen Norton. I knew the deceased—I went there on the Thursday, the day she died—I was present when she died, and assisted in laying her out—I had seen her that same morning, but not lately before that—I found her sitting in the chair—she said she was very ill—I went away at that time—I was sent for a half-past eight o'clock and found her in her daughter's arms vomiting blood—she died in my arms directly afterwards.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18470920-name-1182" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18470920-name-1182" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470920-name-1182" type="surname" value="OLDS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470920-name-1182" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>WILLIAM OLDS.</persName>
                  </hi> I am fourteen years old, and lived with the prisoner and the deceased, my father and mother. On the Saturday night before she died I was at home—my father and mother and I were in the house above nine o'clock, nobody else—my mother had had some money left her—I believe it was kept in a drawer of a cheat of drawers that was there—when my father came home he said, "I want some money"—he was not sober my mother said, "No," she would not give it him; and he took hold of the drawers by the bottom and turned them over—I believe the money was in those drawers—I never saw any there—my father went backwards to get the hammer to break the drawers open—my mother took the hammer out of his hand, and threw it over the pigstye—he then began quarrelling and hitting her—they were both quarrelling—I did not see my mother hit him, nor my father hit her—I went out to fetch a policeman—my mother was then in the front room—she was standing up—I did not see her down upon the ground at all—I went for the policeman because my mother sent me—I did not see my father do anything to her—she was sitting down in a chair when I went for the policeman—my father was standing by the fire-side—he was not quiet, he was making a noise and <hi rend="italic">row</hi>—I did not see him doing any-thing else—I should have seen it if it had been so—my mother hallooed one two or three times, "Run for a policeman," and I did so—I did not see anybody hold my mother round the body.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT.</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Had your mother had her supper at that time? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes—there was some beer there for mother and father's supper—we had not had our supper—the cloth was on the table—we were going to have some bear and oysters—the oysters were on the table—when my father came down he took the beer and shoved it off the table—my mother did nothing upon that—she was not pleased at it—she said, "That did not hurt me"—he then knocked out the candle—there was only one candle there—then he began his <hi rend="italic">row</hi>—I heard him rustling about, and my mother hallooed out two or three times, "Run and fetch the policeman"—she said nothing else.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Recollect yourself; although the prisoner is your father, you must speak the truth; what makes you say he began to make a <hi rend="italic">row</hi> when the candle was out; what did you hear? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Mother said, "Run, he will kill me, he will kill me!"—I did not hear the noise of any blows struck—the table was not turned over—as soon as the <hi rend="italic">row</hi> commenced I ran out—it was quite dark—there was no fire—I do not know what the rustling was about—there was no one else there to rustle about, except my father and mother—when I came back again I had a policeman with me—there was no light then—the policeman turned on his lantern—I went to bed two or three hours after that—I had no supper afterwards—there was a light got before I went to bed—my mother lighted a candle—I did not see any mark on her face that sight—I am quite sure about that—I first saw any mark on her face on the Sunday morning—I was not disturbed in the night after this.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18470920-name-1183" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18470920-name-1183" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470920-name-1183" type="surname" value="SHAW"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470920-name-1183" type="given" value="WILLIAM HACKETT"></interp>WILLIAM HACKETT SHAW</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">police-inspector P.</hi>) I took the prisoner into</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184709200205"></xptr>
               <p>custody on the Sunday night after the deceased's death—he was not sober, and I did not tell him the charge till next morning—I then read it over to him, that it was on suspicion of causing the death of his wife, by violently assaulting her on the night of the 21st of Aug.—he said, "Well, I deny that; I don't recollect striking her at all; but I was very much in liqnor at the time"—the boy William was present at the time the charge was taken, and I said to him, in the prisoner's presence, "Why, you are the boy that came to the station for assistance last Saturday night"—he commenced crying—the prisoner said, "Mind what you are after with that boy"—I repeated the question to the boy, and told him to tell me—he began to cry, and said, "How am I to get my living afterwards?"—I do not recollect that he said anything else.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">to</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. GOWAR.</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> You know the condition in which this woman's lungs were, in point of disease; from your inspection, suppose a person so afflicted was very much exasperated and excited by anger, would that be likely to produce hemorrhage? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> It would not, I think, to the extent which I observed—I think the excitement from anger might not the sufficient.</p>
